{
  "text": "\u03b7(2 \u2212 \u03b7). Here, in the analogy to the case of the nanotube, R represents the curvature [CITATION_1] (the geometrical meaning is also presented in Figure 11 ), A y is connected with the curvature of the carbon bonds. Next, \u03b3 and \u03b3 represent the nearest neighbor and the next-nearest neighbor hopping integrals, respectively and \u03c3 x ( r) = \u03c3 x cos \u03d5 \u2212 \u03c3 z sin \u03d5. Here, \u03c3 x , \u03c3 y , \u03c3 z are the Pauli matrices, but (unlikely the \u03c4 matrices) this time they are connected with SOC. The parameters p and \u03b4 are connected with the hopping integrals and the atomic potential, respectively. Their closer explanation can be also found in [CITATION_2] . The following choice of their values was used: \u03b4 is of the order between 10 \u22123 and 10 \u22122 , ",
  "correct_citation": {
